Because the question is not really **“is 10 speeds too many?”** — it is **“was the TC10 the right solution for the Class 8 market?”**

The short answer is: **there is a market for many forward ratios in commercial trucks, but the market overwhelmingly chose AMTs, not a torque-converter full automatic like the TC10.** Today the mainstream heavy-truck market is built around AMTs such as Detroit DT12, Eaton Cummins Endurant, Volvo I-Shift, Mack mDRIVE, and PACCAR TX-12/TX-18. OEMs market these specifically for efficiency and on-highway use, and Volvo now explicitly says AMTs have become the industry standard in North America. ([Freightliner][1])

So why didn’t OEMs and fleets really embrace the TC10?

**1. Allison aimed it at the wrong slice of the market for big volume.**
Allison’s own filings repeatedly said it had **very limited exposure to the Class 8 line-haul tractor market** because **lower-priced manuals and AMTs generally met those trucks’ needs**. It positioned the TC10 for a narrower “metro tractor” or mixed urban/highway duty cycle, not for the bread-and-butter long-haul fleet market. ([SEC][2])

**2. Long-haul fleets care brutally about fuel economy and total cost.**
AMTs became attractive because they keep the efficiency of a manual-style geartrain while removing driver shift variability. Industry coverage from that period notes AMTs’ principal virtue was fuel economy, and OEMs today still sell DT12, Endurant, I-Shift, and TX-12 as efficiency-focused products. In long steady-state highway cruising, that matters more than the smoother launch and shift feel of a full automatic. ([Heavy Duty Trucking][3])

**3. The TC10 was more expensive than the alternatives.**
A 2014 HDT test-drive report said Navistar noted the TC10 was priced about **15–20% more than Eaton UltraShift products**, which themselves already cost thousands more than comparable manuals. That is a hard sell in large fleets unless the TCO case is overwhelming. ([Heavy Duty Trucking][4])

**4. OEM support existed, but it was limited and late.**
The TC10 first appeared with Navistar/International, later expanded to PACCAR models, and then International LT with Cummins X15. So it was not that “no OEM wanted it” — some did offer it — but it never became the default powertrain path across the major line-haul platforms the way DT12, I-Shift, mDRIVE, and Endurant did. ([Heavy Duty Trucking][5])

**5. Allison eventually pulled the plug.**
In March 2020, Allison ended **new production** of the TC10 and kept only replacement/ReTran support. That tells you the business case did not scale the way Allison hoped. ([Heavy Duty Trucking][6])

Your instinct about “10 speeds” is directionally right, but the market answered it differently:

* **Yes, commercial trucks absolutely want lots of ratios.**
* **No, they did not particularly want a TC10-style full automatic for mainstream Class 8 linehaul.**

In practice, the market migrated toward **12-, 13-, and 18-speed AMTs**, because they delivered:

* enough ratio coverage,
* better highway efficiency,
* lower cost than a full automatic,
* strong engine/transmission integration from the OEM,
* and easier driver operation than manuals. ([Freightliner][1])

So the clean conclusion is:

**The TC10 did not fail because “10 speeds aren’t useful.” It struggled because the dominant Class 8 market wanted the ratio coverage and driver ease of an automatic, but with the fuel-efficiency and cost structure of an AMT.** The winners were DT12, Endurant, I-Shift, mDRIVE, and TX-series AMTs — not because they had fewer gears, but because they matched the economics of long-haul trucking better. ([SEC][2])

